<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-11-16T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-11-16T09:00:00-05:00" n="59" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 296/700: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-11-16T15:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">November 16,
                                        1924—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 3:10
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>174. Your no. 130, November 6, 5 p.m.<note n="72" xml:id="d59fn72">Not
                                printed.</note> I understand that the Secretary General of the
                            Italian Foreign Office has stated that he sees no reason why Italian
                            delegation should not support American position for payment of claims. I
                            have advised Logan.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Summerlin</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>